-- Crude Oil Options Volatility Slumps as Futures Post Weekly Gain
-- B y   C h r i s t i n e   H a r v e y
-- 2013-04-26T19:52:21Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-26/crude-oil-options-volatility-slumps-as-futures-post-weekly-gain.html
Crude oil options volatility
slumped for a seventh day as the underlying futures posted the
biggest weekly gain since June and remained in the $85- to $98-
a-barrel range itâ€™s held it since mid-November.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
June, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 20.54 percent at 3:20 p.m. on the  New
York Mercantile Exchange , down from 20.66 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate oil for June delivery climbed 5.7
percent to $93 a barrel on the Nymex since April 19.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
June $85 puts, which increased 12 cents to 70 cents a barrel on
volume of 2,811 contracts at 3:28 p.m. June $90 puts were
second-most active on volume of 2,767 lots. They advanced 10
cents to 77 cents a barrel.  Puts, or bets that crude futures will fall, accounted for
57 percent of electronic trading volume. Bearish bets made up 53
percent on volume of 188,860 contracts yesterday.  June $98 calls were the most-active options in the previous
session, with 8,999 lots changing hands. They gained 23 cents to
43 cents a barrel. June $97 calls rose 34 cents to 62 cents a
barrel on 7,258 contracts.  Open interest was highest for June $80 puts with 42,109
contracts. Next were December $105 calls with 35,905 lots and
December $110 calls with 35,115.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-
outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
